sentences: Reice Hamel (June 18, 1920 – October 1, 1986) was an American Audio Recording engineer.
Reice Hamel was born in the Lower East Side of Manhattan, New York City on June 18, 1920.
His mother Freida Bernstein, and Father Leo Hamel, were Jewish immigrants from Austria who came to America in the early 1900s.
In 1956, he became interested in audio engineering and Magnetic Tape Recording and decided to try it as a business.
In the 1950s, San Francisco was a hotbed of talent and in small nightclubs like the Hungry I, Purple Onion, Jazz Workshop, Curran Theatre, the Cellar, and the Blackhawk.

On any given evening there would be comedians, singers, and bands of all types.
In 1963, at the Hungry I club, a young teenage singer made her debut, recorded by Reice Hamel, her name was Barbra Streisand.
These recordings are of exceptional sound quality and in 1962, Seymour Solomon, of Vanguard Records wrote a letter to thank Reice Hamel for the tapes.
